@REM ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~  INTRODUCTION  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

@NODE "INTR_DESCRIP" "Program description"

  @{B}Introduction@{UB}
  ------------

    GiambyNetGrabber is a freeware program which allows to recursively
    download, update and manage files from the internet.

    I decided to create this program when I noticed the huge limitations
    which web browsers have in some tasks, such as link handling or the slow
    and not so smart download process.

    But what mostly induced me to create this program was the observation
    that, actually, there's no web-mirroring tool on Amiga offering a
    graphical interface and other useful options.

    While developing it I also realized that GiambyNetGrabber is, maybe, the
    ideal complement of a web browser while browsing the web: it allows the
    rationalization of online times, making the simultaneous update of daily
    visited pages possible, as well as resuming interrupted downloads
    through the use of the HTTP/1.1 protocol.

    Here is a summary of the main program features:

  · @{"MUI" link "POL_MUI"} interface;
    · Drag & Drop;
    · AppWindow;
    · Context sensitive online help;
    · Customizable images;
  · Multiple processes, totally asynchronous;
  · More than 40 recognized and configurable HTML tags;
  · Internal support for filenames longer than 30 characters or containing 
    characters not supported by the filesystem.

    Supported protocols:

  · HTTP/1.1
    · high speed
    · restricted download
    · interrupted download resuming

@ENDNODE
@NODE "INTR_REQUIRE" "Required resources for the installation"

    GiambyNetGrabber has been developed on an A1200/030, 2+36Mb, 2Gb HD, CD.
    The recommended configuration is a 68020 CPU and 4Mb of Fast RAM. The
    program has been tested locally, on an Apache server.

    @{B}Required software@{UB}
    -----------------

    · Kickstart 3.0/Workbench 3.0 or higher.
    · MUI 3.8 or higher.
    · NList.mcc and NListView.mcc MUI classes by Gilles Masson.
      (@{I}included in the program archive@{UI})
    · AmiTCP compatible stack (AmiTCP, Miami, TermiteTCP).


@ENDNODE
@NODE "INTR_INSTALL" "Installation"

    @{B}Installation@{UB}
    ------------

    There's nothing special about the program installation: when you're sure
    the @{"required software" link "INTR_REQUIRE"} has been correctly installed,
    just run the proper installation script.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "INTR_STEP2STEP" "Step-by-step guide"

    @{B}Step-by-step guide@{UB}
    ------------------

    Here follows a short explanation on how to execute your first download
    with GiambyNetGrabber.

    After loading the program for the first time, you'd better set the
    @{"preferences" link "WIN_PREFS"} so that you can use the program at its best,
    according to your personal needs.

    Once you have set your preferences, you should first of all create a new
    project by pressing the @{"New" link "New_Button"} button (a new project will be
    created, named "untitled.gnp") or the @{"Open" link "Open_Button"} button, which will
    open a file requester where you can type the name of the project you
    want to create (don't forget the ".gnp" suffix).

    When the new project window has been opened, you have to insert some new
    URLs by selecting the "URL/Add" menu item: a new window will be opened,
    named "URL properties". The program allows for the addition or editing
    of more than one URL at the same time: this possibility is especially
    useful when coupled with the drag&drop feature of string gadgets.

    In the "URL properties" window you can insert the URL, an optional
    descriptive title, the authorization parameters and other parameters for
    the recursive download.

    After inserting one or more URLs, just press the @{"Grab" link "Grab_Button"} button
    to start the download process: a new window will be opened, containing
    some fill gadgets which indicate the download status. Dragging one of
    these gadgets over the @{"Stop" link "Stop_Button"} button you can abort the download
    of a single URL.

@ENDNODE

@REM ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~  MAIN WINDOW  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

@NODE "WIN_MAIN" "Main window"

    @{B}Main window@{UB}
    -----------

    This is the only program window which always remains active. Through
    this window's menus and gadgets you can reach the main project
    management functions, which always affect the current project or the
    last used one.

    Here follows a description of the gadgets and their functions:

                @{" New           " link "New_Button"    }
                @{" Close         " link "Open_Button"   }
                @{" Save          " link "Save_Button"   }

                @{" Grab          " link "Grab_Button"   }
                @{" Stop          " link "Stop_Button"   }
                @{" Update        " link "Update_Button" }

@ENDNODE
@NODE "New_Button" "New project"

    @{B}New project@{UB}
    -----------

    This button opens a new project window.

@TOC "WIN_MAIN"
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Open_Button"  "Open project"

    @{B}Open project@{UB}
    ------------

    This button opens an existing project or creates a new one. You can also
    open a project file by dragging its icon from a Workbench window and
    dropping it on this button.

@TOC "WIN_MAIN"
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Save_Button"  "Save project"

    @{B}Save project@{UB}
    ------------

    Saves the currently active project.

@TOC "WIN_MAIN"
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Grab_Button" "Grab"

    @{B}Start the download process@{UB}
    --------------------------

    When pressing this button, URLs in the current project will start to be
    downloaded. You can also start the download for more than one project:
    just activate another project window and press the Grab button again.

@TOC "WIN_MAIN"
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Stop_Button" "Stop"

    @{B}Stop the download process@{UB}
    --------------------------

    Pressing this button you will stop the current download process.

    You can also drag the fill gadgets indicating the download status on
    this button, this will stop the related single download process.

@TOC "WIN_MAIN"
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Update_Button"  "Update"

    @{B}Update the currently active project@{UB}
    -----------------------------------

    When pressing this button the program will first clear the aborted or
    failed URLs, and will then start the download process (see @{"grab" link Grab_Button}).

@TOC "WIN_MAIN"
@ENDNODE

@REM ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~  PROJECT WINDOW  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

@NODE "WIN_PROJECT" "Project window"

    @{B}Project window@{UB}
    --------------

    Through this window you can manage single projects. Three buttons
    are provided to add, edit and remove single URLs. The window mostly
    consists of an URL list, where the main informations about the URL are
    shown.

    S (Status) URL status (represented by some intuitive icons)
    URL        The URL
    Type       Type of data associated to the URL
    Size       File size
    Date       Datestamp of the URL found on the server

@NEXT "WIN_EDIT"
@ENDNODE

@REM ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~  EDIT WINDOW  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

@NODE "WIN_EDIT" "Adding or editing the URLs"

    @{B}URL properties window@{UB}
    ---------------------

                Global:
                @{" URL           " link "URL_String"      }
                @{" Title         " link "Title_String"    }
                @{" Name          " link "Name_String"     }
                @{" Password      " link "Passwd_String"   }

                @{" Links         " link "EDIT_Links"      }

                @{" HTML          " link "EDIT_HTML"       }

                @{" Download      " link "EDIT_Download"   }

@ENDNODE
@NODE "URL_String" "URL insertion"

    @{B}URL insertion@{UB}
    -------------

    You must enter in this gadget the URL you want to download.

    The program uses an automatic correction algorithm to prevent the
    insertion of incorrectly typed URLs.

@TOC "WIN_EDIT"
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Title_String" "Title"

    @{B}Insertion of a descriptive title@{UB}
    --------------------------------

    Here you can enter a descriptive title for the URL.

@TOC "WIN_EDIT"
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Name_String" "Name"

    @{B}Authorization name@{UB}
    ------------------

    Here you can enter the name for the URL authorization.

@TOC "WIN_EDIT"
@ENDNODE
@NODE "Passwd_String" "Password"

    @{B}Authorization password@{UB}
    ----------------------

    Here you can enter the password for the URL authorization.

@TOC "WIN_EDIT"
@ENDNODE
@NODE "EDIT_Links" "Links"

    @{B}Restricting links@{UB}
    -----------------

    Here you can limit the number of links that GiambyNetGrabber will
    recursively follow inside an HTML document.

    Through the cycle gadget, you can do a first choice about the server:

        · @{B}No servers@{UB}: no link will be followed.
        · @{B}Same server@{UB}: only links referring to contents located on
                       the same server as the starting page will be
                       followed.
        · @{B}Other server@{UB}: only links referring to contents located on
                        servers different from the one where the starting
                        page resides will be followed.
        · @{B}All servers@{UB}: all links will be followed.

    Then, through the numeric gadget, you can decide how deeply any
    sub-links will have to be followed.

@TOC "WIN_EDIT"
@ENDNODE
@NODE "EDIT_HTML" "HTML"

    @{B}Customizing the HTML parser@{UB}
    ---------------------------

    GiambyNetGrabber provides an advanced asynchronous HTML parser which
    guarantees optimum speed and customizing possibilities.
    In this section you can limit the HTML tags taken into account by the
    parser, so to avoid downloading undesired files.

    In the @{B}Include@{UB} section you can define which HTML subset will
    have to be taken into account by the parser (HTML 2.0, 3.2 or 4.0), and
    decide if Internet Explorer, Netscape or other extensions have to be
    included.

    In the @{B}Exclude@{UB} section you can deactivate tag recognition for
    tags defining images, backgrounds, java applets or objects inserted
    inside the HTML text.

    To see a complete list of HTML tags supported by the GiambyNetGrabber
    parser please click @{"here" link "HTML_TAGS"}.

@TOC "WIN_EDIT"
@ENDNODE
@NODE "EDIT_Download" "Downloads"

    @{B}Restricting downloads@{UB} (Not yet implemented)
    ---------------------

    If you activate this gadget GiambyNetGrabber will only download files of
    size smaller than the specified one, whenever obtaining the file size
    from the server is possible.

@TOC "WIN_EDIT"
@ENDNODE

@REM ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~  PREFS WINDOW  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

@NODE "WIN_PREFS" "Global settings"

    @{B}Global settings@{UB}
    ---------------

    In this window you can customize the program.

    Under "HTTP" you can set:
    · An eventual proxy server, together with the proper port number and
      authorization password.
    · Global settings for the download tasks:
        · Buffer: this is the size of the buffer which every single task
          will allocate and use when downloading a file.
        · Reconnect: this is the number of times every single task will
          attempt to reconnect before returning an error.
        · Delay: this is the number of seconds to wait before attempting to
          restore a failed connection.

    Under "User data" you can set:
    · The e-mail address which, when inserted, will be sent together with
      each URL download request.

@ENDNODE

@REM ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~  LPREFS WINDOW  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

@NODE "WIN_LPREFS" "Project preferences"

    @{B}Project preferences@{UB}
    -------------------

    Using this window you can customize the project. These settings will be
    saved together with the project.

    @{B}Download@{UB} represents the directory which will be used to save
    files downloaded from Internet.
    @{B}Indexfile name@{UB} is the name of the file which is used as an
    index for URLs like "http://www.domain.org/".
    @{B}Maximum number of connections@{UB} is the maximum number of
    simultaneous connections which the program will be allowed to activate
    when downloading the project URLs.

@ENDNODE

@REM ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~  GRAB   WINDOW  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

@NODE "WIN_GRAB" "Network status"

    @{B}Network status@{UB}
    --------------

    Using this window you can monitor the download tasks' activity.

    Closing this window has the same effect as pressing the @{"Stop" link "Stop_Button"} button.

@ENDNODE

@REM ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~  ADVANCED SETTINGS  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

@NODE "ADVANCED_SETTINGS" "Advanced settings"

    @{B}Advanced settings@{UB}
    -----------------

    I decided to describe some of GiambyNetGrabber's customizable features
    in this section because, probably, less experienced users could
    encounter some difficulties when trying to customize the program parts
    we will be analyzing here.

        @{B}Customizing images@{UB}

    First of all, you can make the program use custom images rather than the
    ones built into the executables: this can be done by putting some IFF
    ILBM image files in the "images" drawer (please pay attention to the
    size of the images and to their number of colours!), using the following
    names:

    About.img    : replaces the image in the About requester

    New.img      : replaces the "New" button image
    Open.img     : replaces the "Open" button image
    Save.img     : replaces the "Save" button image
    Grab.img     : replaces the "Grab" button image
    Update.img   : replaces the "Update" button image
    StopGrab.img : replaces the "Stop" button image

    URL status images:

    Clear.img        : URL for which no action is being taken
    Grabbing.img     : URL being downloaded
    Grabbed.img      : URL successfully downloaded
    Decoding.img     : URL being decoded
    Editing.img      : URL being edited
    Interrupted.img  : aborted URL
    Error.img        : general error

        @{B}Customizing memory pools@{UB}

    GiambyNetGrabber uses a single memory pool, shared by many tasks, and in
    some situations it can be useful being allowed to modify its size; to
    this purpose you can set the following tooltypes:

    POOLPUDDLESIZE  : sets the puddle size
    POOLTRESHSIZE   : sets the threshold size
    KEYFILE         : specifies the keyfile name

@ENDNODE
@NODE "URL2FILE" "URL -> file name conversion"

    @{B}Converting from an URL to a file name@{UB}
    -------------------------------------

    In this paragraph we talk about the method used by the program to
    convert the URLs so that they can be saved to disk, organized in a
    subdirectory scheme.

    The program simply creates a directory named like the server, and then
    creates any subdirectories needed until the filename is reached; the
    file will be saved in the last created directory.

    When the URL contains characters not supported by the file system, or
    when the name of the file (or the directory) is longer than 30
    characters, the program makes some conversions which can be summarized
    with the following source code (to be considered as protected by the GNU
    license):


char *
UrlToDos (unsigned char *url)
{
  unsigned char *s, *tmp, t;
  ULONG i = 0, r = 0;

  for (; url[i] != '\0'; i++)
    {
      if (isndos (url[i])) // Checks whether the character is
        r++;               // not supported by the file-system
   }

  if ((s = (char *) malloc ((i += (r * 2) + 1))))
    {
      tmp = s;

      for (; *url != '\0'; url++)
        {
          if (isndos (*url))
            {
              t = *url;                   // Converts the non-standard
              *tmp++ = '^';               // character into a standard
              *tmp++ = hexd[t >> 4];      // representation of the
              *tmp++ = hexd[t & '\x0f'];  // same character
            }
          else
            *tmp++ = *url;
        }

      *tmp = '\0';
    }

  #define BUFFERSIZE 1048*8

  if (--i > 30)   // Is the file/dir name longer than 30 characters?
    {
      BPTR filein;
      char readbuffer[BUFFERSIZE];
      char filename[31];
      char bufn[100];
      int n = 0;
      BOOL found = FALSE;

      memset (bufn, 0, sizeof (bufn));

      // Truncates the filename at 28 characters plus some trailing chars

      filename[0] = s[0];
      filename[1] = s[1];
      filename[2] = s[2];
      filename[3] = s[3];
      filename[4] = s[4];
      filename[5] = s[5];
      filename[6] = s[6];
      filename[7] = s[7];
      filename[8] = s[8];
      filename[9] = s[8];
      filename[10] = s[10];
      filename[11] = s[11];
      filename[12] = s[12];
      filename[13] = s[13];
      filename[14] = s[14];
      filename[15] = s[15];
      filename[16] = s[16];
      filename[17] = s[17];
      filename[18] = s[18];
      filename[19] = s[19];
      filename[20] = s[20];
      filename[21] = s[21];
      filename[22] = s[22];
      filename[23] = s[23];
      filename[24] = s[24];
      filename[25] = s[25];
      filename[26] = s[26];
      filename[27] = s[27];
      filename[28] = '^';
      filename[29] = 'i';
      filename[30] = '\0';

      // Searches an index for the filename

      if ((filein = Open (filename, MODE_READWRITE)))
        {
          while (FGets (filein, readbuffer, BUFFERSIZE) != NULL)
            {
              if (strncmp (s, readbuffer, i) == 0)
                {
                  n = atoi (readbuffer + i + 1);
                  found = TRUE;
                  break;
                }
              else
                {
                  if ((tmp = strchr (readbuffer, '=')))
                    {
                      n = atoi (++tmp);
                      if (n > 99)
                        n = 99;
                      bufn[n] = 1;
                    }
                }
            }

          if (!found)
            {
              for (i = 0; i < 100; i++)
                {
                  if (bufn[i] == 0)
                    {
                      n = i;
                      break;
                    }
                }

              i = sprintf (readbuffer, "%s=%ld\n", s, n);
              FPuts (filein, readbuffer);
            }

          Close (filein);

          if ((tmp = (char *) malloc (30)))
            {
              strncpy (tmp, s, 30);
              sprintf (tmp + 26, "^i%ld", n);
            }

          free (s);
          s = tmp;

        }
    }

  return (s);
}


@ENDNODE

